{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2988ccda-996a-4922-b738-770fed5ddfb6","content":"After a .NET SDK update, run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update, since workload manifests and packs may have changed.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the **currently pinned versions** of workloads. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't fetch newer versions. It won't resolve version mismatches caused by an SDK update.\n\n**TL;DR:** `dotnet workload update` aligns your workloads with the new SDK. `dotnet workload repair` just re-downloads what you already had.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eff2d701-b11e-48db-99fb-33ac97cadcbd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question—no tools needed.","outputTokens":239,"requestId":"B7DD:203C31:1325B7:18B156:69FFD72F"},"id":"c3c0c74f-f06f-4e8b-ac0a-8418d2c21cde","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:54:13.500Z","parentId":"35d68228-3bb9-475d-b267-516c9f001b74"}
